snippet.textDisplay:
Hi Chris,

Yours is the only review of the Rise of Skywalker I elected to watch because the other reviews reactions came off as hyperbolic for the Last Jedi (which I enjoyed unequivocally), and after a while it started affecting my emotional health so I've also left the fandom. I genuinely appreciate you being even-handed about it, because I don't want to avoid talking about Star Wars, but I also like my health and happiness.

I do want to bring up my perspective on these films (which I enjoyed) as a counter and an observation:
First, reading it thematically, JJ Abrams leaned into some elements of the Last Jedi's themes: It is the family's we choose that matter, not the ones we are born into and "we win by protecting the things we love, not by attacking the things we hate". And those threads are what drive the film's conflict.

But also, it's clear that JJ Abrams looked at the preceding 8 films and felt that it made sense, in retconning it as the "Skywalker Saga" that Palpatine was the monster/villain of that saga; given that he's run things from the shadows, Abrams used it - and member berries - to bring him back to wrap up the story in a bow. He also leaned into the final chapter apocalyptic battle element. I will concede that this was done at Disney's behest so that they can expand the universe to other stories, but I had no problem with it, mostly because Abrams is a reasonably competent (if often shallow) storyteller. One of the major tropes of longform storytelling like this is the final part has to be suitably apocalyptic, and the sith/jedi dynamic has been the ongoing thread pulling it together. So I bought it.

And, further, this film - like the preceding two - took notes from that George Lucas's quote about the film series being a poem where each film rhymes. If you track the plot beats for this film, you can see it is rhyming with Return of the Jedi, just as The Last Jedi rhymed with Empire. DJ and Cantobight definitely took notes from Lando Calrissian/Cloud City/Bespin plot points, but not exactly the same beats. But, being the final rhyme of this poem, it also tries to encapsulate all the rhymes from the preceding film and look back on them. For the record, I don't think it's a perfect film and don't find it did a transcendantl job of closing the series. But I was satisfied, and so feel compelled to defend it.

But to the other, major points: watching those videos had an impact on your opinion of this film. I have observed that the people who have spent the most time on youtube with those videos had the strongest negative reaction to it. I do not think it is a coincidence. it's a kind of priming, where you are going to be looking for errors more than you would have. The people who are casual fans, or don't watch those critiques struck me as the happiest with the end product.

And I do think that the fanbase shares the onus of the legacy of these films. Disney is doing what is in its best interest, and I'm not going to blame it for listening to the fanbase. But the fanbase has been consistently and aggressively toxic since the release of the prequel trilogies. The evidence is overwhelming: George Lucas sold the franchise, Jar Jar Binks actor was pushed to being suicidal, Daisy Ridley and Kelly Marie Tran have left social media ENTIRELY, and that's only the most obvious damage. So, to an extent, I think the fandom should act on its capacity for self-reflection to see what role they played. They won't, and they can't, but I would love if they did.

And one final point: the original trilogy was not always a trilogy. There are plenty of moments that demonstrate that. It was planned by Lucas, and others expressed his vision. I'm sure you know this. But Star Wars has always been a corporatized entity, that has - at its best - relied on a committee to tell its best stories. So I find most of the complaints about Disney to be bad faith, or reflective of maturing, and not a function of the film's inherent failings.

And, also, The Empire Strikes back was poorly received when it was released, it just didn't have the internet.

Again, thank you for being decent about this. I am genuinely sorry that this film and franchise have become a sore spot for you. It really breaks my heart that you aren't able to enjoy this franchise as much as you once did.

And, if you actually read this. Thank you. I don't expect it, but you're decent, so maybe there is a chance.

Peace, my friend

To me, it felt like an honest (and hard working, I'm sure...) effort to 'clean the damage' done by the previous film. I 'blame' the (most probable) lack of focus on the integrity of a story to be told across 3 movies... To me, Episode IX has 'heart' on the 'effort' that was done in order to 'complete' the lack of coherence from the story being told... Even though it SURE isn't ideal, that stands for something. I'll continue hoping for a SW movie to 'compete' with Ep. V... Probably not in my lifetime. ;) Nevertheless, a joyful Christmas for all !

snippet.textDisplay: As an older Star Wars fan, my experience is different. I watched the originals at the cinema as a very young boy. I watched these three with my twin boys who are now 11. So rather than watching it purely through the eyes of an old fan desperate for the films to meet my childhood expectations (impossible), I also see through through the eyes of a child with less expectations and no exposure to this type of social media. My kids loved this one, if not the previous two. It was a fun film. But where will it rank in their eyes when they are my age. I hope they remember it. But they will certainly remember Avengers: Endgame which was the film of the year for kids. It was the film event of their childhood. For kids now it would the Marvel films are what Star Was was to my generation. I loved watching these new Star Wars films with my lads, however my expectations had dropped before I saw this one. I just wanted to enjoy the film with my boys. But we were all excited before and after Endgame. Maybe freed from the old characters and the expectations of older guys hoping to recreate the feelings of childhood, Star Wars can now build a world that the youth of today can call their own and fall in love with.

I feel your pain stuckman but let me paint this in a different way. If you like batman, you respect the Adam west, Tim Burton, and Chris Nolan versions( also the animated series). If one person says "anything after 1966 is not a real batman movie/show", most people would look at them crazy, especially anyone who grew up with the other versions.

Taking that example with star wars, the prequels are the first ones some people saw, the original sequel was what most people saw, and this new trilogy is the most recent. Because they were released from 2015-2019 in the age of social media, me too, and instant gratification and reaction they will always be scrutinized more, although phantom menace got a pretty bad reception in its times,it still ages well because it gave us Darth maul, double bladed lightsabre, and pod races (among other things). It added to the lore and expanded but always entertained. Did it surpass new hope? Absolutely not. Is it regarded as an OK star wars flick? Yeah. I think it's accepted not loved or hated.

Now with this sequel trilogy I know there are problems (like Alot),but you can't deny it gave us Alot such as kylo Ren, Reys origins and ending to her story,a storm trooper turning good, new weapons, concepts (war profiteering in last jedi and horses in rise of Skywalker), bb8, babo Frick, New force powers, jedi sacred texts... Etc. There was so much added that its gonna be remembered more fondly in years to come. Just think, jj Abraham's had to put together a film from the last jedi that basically wrote him into a corner and we still got something coherent and entertaining. Couldn't ask for more.

Wait, if Palpatine was Anakin's "father," that makes her Ben's cousin. So cousin romance is a thing in their universe now?
Thank you for the great review. We aren't Disney boycotting, because they have some great properties in their ownership, but we are Lucas Films boycotting after the garbage storm of Last Jedi. So I was looking for some clarifications without buying a ticket.
George Lucas said in an interview that he wanted to make 9 films, and at the end of the 9th it would be a scene of the droids telling the Skywalker family saga to the grandkids. When they removed him, they removed this continuity and destroyed the integrity of what he built.
Also Palpatine using the force to send his soul to his clones was taken from the books, where at one point they have to go hunting the clones down to stop him. There was also the factions of the empire who didn't know it fell and had to be fought.
Honestly for me the idea of Leia and Han naming their son Ben made no sense to me. In the books Luke names his son Ben after Obi Wan, and that makes sense. He was around when Luke grew up, his was his first teacher, and he communed with Obi Wan's force ghost. He was important in Luke's life. But he never met Leia, and Han spent very little time with him, so exactly why did they name their only child after him? It was like The Force Awakens wanted to grab the "remember Obi Wan" member berries but didn't really think it through.
